@EmilyWowkAgain I am here, safe and sound, actually I focusing on our Educational service for members.
We had a very positive start of 2021, with our model constantly pointing to Aggressive Long ($TQQQ - $QQQ) since nov4th2020.
We are +67.5% since then.

@Pope_Chadi, I agree with @autogreg
$TQQQ was born in 2010, the very best time to get benefit from the long run which is still ongoing.
During 2000-2001 or 2008-2009 the drawdowns would have been approx -78% and -94%

@kickplate66 Not using Swaps / Options / Future contracts.
We use ETfs which still are derivatives replying the indexes NasdaqComp and S&P500, with leverage ( $UPRO $TQQQ) or with no leverage ( $SPY or $QQQ), this is up to followers to choose.
There are many other ETFs which are basically the same, as $SPXL or  others. They are not much different, we only mention the most popular.

@Strumok @TKPTrader you should use logarithmic scales only when the variable is a value, increasing in time like the points of $SPX  .
Percentages and ratios, by definition move between 0 - 1  or 0 - 100.
Log scales make no sense here

@BruteR9 @Twit2018 Today has been a demonstration of the priciples inside the HST model: it does not follows the one-days alerts, which are often false positives.
It combines TA and FA and tries to avoid only big corrections or bear market. During uncertain times it usually stays invested with ETFs based on $SPX in order to reduce risk ($UPRO or $SPY).
Cash is suggested for 10% of the times only.

@Gataman @m3s Note: in long term a Buy&Hold strategy based on 3x ETFs is very, very risky, possibly mortal.
Such ETFs as $TQQQ did not exist at that time, but if they did, they would not have survived to main bear markets as 2001 and 2008, and others.
We've backtested them, and here are their ugly, virtual performances.

@m3s you mean this holding $TQQQ, right?
because $UPRO has never been at 62.78$,and the HST model is pointing to Moderate Long since many days.
What was your date of purchase?

@GloryTwits actual position of our model is moderate long
Meaning $UPRO or $SPY according to which variant is applied.
Different variants of the HSTmodel have different yields and risk levels

@GloryTwits nope. The HST model shifts among Aggressive Long / moderate long / cash
It does not apply a simple Buy&Hold strategy on $TQQQ.
Buying&holding 3x leveraged ETFs can be a very risky strategy. In case of main drops of market those ETFs can lose almost all the capital.

@mohawkman2 We are long term investors, and do could not consider to invest in something like this picture.
Having $SQQQ if you expect a drop of the index makes sense if you are a scalper or short-term trader.
It is a very different perspective indeed.

@WinningNewsletters drawdown and yields are strictly connected. You could reduce ma in drawdown with quick stop loss, but this is also reducing the yields.
We think that the best way to reduce drawdown is using 2x or 1x ETFs instead of 3x. The variant 5 is giving an average yield of 17,1%  and max dd of 22% using $QQQ  and $SPY 
Also, note that only 6 years on 48 have been negative

@RobinHoodRatt sorry, no. The model can be applied with 3x leveraged ETFs as $TQQQ and $UPRO or with non leveraged ETFs.
The first modality generated max drawdowns of 54% which is already something for aggressive investors.
Remember also that signals come only once a day. I would not risk trading options on these conditions.

@brendon_chan yes, That's correct.
